{
  "doc_id": "60279",
  "text": "Male R. argentiventer had significantly larger home ranges than females during the breeding season, but no differences between sexes were found during the nonbreeding season, regardless of weather. Similar results have been reported for other rodents [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Male maturity and intermale competition typically precede the seasonal availability of receptive females (Anderson 1989) . [CITATION_5] and [CITATION_6] suggested that during the breeding season, males of Apodemus sylvaticus, similar to many other rodents, maximize chances of encountering estrous females by covering large areas.",
